_50x51_19.jpg 1390w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"kb-slide-item kb-gallery-carousel-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item-inner\"><figure class=\"kb-gallery-figure kb-gallery-item-has-link kadence-blocks-gallery-item-hide-caption\"><a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20.jpg\" class=\"kb-gallery-item-link\"><div class=\"kb-gal-image-radius\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-image-contain\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20-1024x652.jpg\" width=\"1024\" height=\"652\" alt=\"\" data-full-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20.jpg\" data-light-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20.jpg\" data-id=\"247\" data-link=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?attachment_id=247\" class=\"wp-image-247 skip-lazy\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20-1024x652.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20-300x191.jpg 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20-768x489.jpg 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/S9_04A1_DC_50x51_20.jpg 1390w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The first thing we can appreciate is a non negligible amount of garbage. This clearly introduces noise in the TCT measurements, however it is hard to quantize this noise. Another interesting thing we can see is the presence of circular structures on the metallic strips for the zoomed images. I don&#8217;t know what they are and\/or how they affect the measurements in the TCT.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In order at least rule where the jitter is coming from, I took one of these pictures and extracted the intensity profile. This I did using the nice program <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/sites.google.com\/cfa.harvard.edu\/saoimageds9\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/sites.google.com\/cfa.harvard.edu\/saoimageds9\" target=\"_blank\">SAOImageDS9<\/a>. Below there is a screenshot I took while extracting the intensity profile:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-01_19-31-27-1024x791.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-250\" width=\"984\" height=\"760\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-01_19-31-27-1024x791.png 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-01_19-31-27-300x232.png 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-01_19-31-27-768x593.png 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-01_19-31-27.png 1389w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 984px) 100vw, 984px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>I took this profile and plotted it against the \\( \\text{spaghetti profile}(y) \\) I presented before, and this is what I got:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/htmlpreview.github.io\/?https:\/\/github.com\/SengerM\/html-github-hosting\/blob\/main\/210202%20on%20the%20spacial%20characteristics%20of%20the%20TCT\/20210201000000_spaghetti_diode_in_microscope\/processed_by_script_process_microscope_picture\/Intensity%20profile%20in%20the%20picture.html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"555\"><\/iframe>\n\n\n\n<p>From here I concluded that the pitch of 80 \u00b5m and the width of the metallic strips of 20 \u00b5m in the spaghetti diode can be regarded as &#8220;perfect&#8221;, in the sense that the jitter I observed before cannot be coming from an &#8220;non-perfect construction&#8221; of the spaghetties in the diode.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Obtaining the beam shape by deconvolution <\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Since the \\( \\text{collected charge model}(y) \\) model is not fitting very good to the data, I proceeded in a different way to obtain the profile of the laser. Basically I &#8220;deconvoluted&#8221; it from the data by doing the convolution of the data with the &#8220;inverse spaghetti diode profile&#8221;. If the random jitter component were not present then we could just deconvolute the two signals &#8220;measured charge&#8221; with \\( \\text{collected charge model}(y) \\). Because the random jitter is there, if we do this we will get a single peak for the laser which has somehow averaged all these random contributions. To avoid this what I did is to deconvolute the measured collected charge with a single &#8220;inverse spaghetti window&#8221;, basically a non periodic square signal defined as<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-mathml-mathmlblock\">\\[ \\text{inverse spaghetti}(y)=\\left\\{ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 1 &amp;  &amp; \\text{if }0&lt;y&lt;20\\ \\text{\u00b5m}\\\\\n &amp; 0 &amp;  &amp; \\text{else}\n\\end{aligned}\n\\right. \\]<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>By doing the convolution between this inverse spaghetti and the collected charge, we should get an approximation of the laser profile at each fringe:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/htmlpreview.github.io\/?https:\/\/github.com\/SengerM\/html-github-hosting\/blob\/main\/210202%20on%20the%20spacial%20characteristics%20of%20the%20TCT\/20210129171131_spagetti_y_scan\/processed_by_script_extract_beam_shape\/Single%20peak%20deconvolution.html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"555\"><\/iframe>\n\n\n\n<p>Keeping the simple model of a Gaussian function for the laser, we can fit it to each of these peaks:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/htmlpreview.github.io\/?https:\/\/github.com\/SengerM\/html-github-hosting\/blob\/main\/210202%20on%20the%20spacial%20characteristics%20of%20the%20TCT\/20210129171131_spagetti_y_scan\/processed_by_script_extract_beam_shape\/Gaussians%20fitted%20to%20each%20peak.html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"555\"><\/iframe>\n\n\n\n<p>We can see that the agreement is nice. From this analysis I combined the \\( \\sigma \\) of each fit into a single \\( \\sigma_\\text{average} \\) and, up to now, it is my best estimation for the shape of the laser beam:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/htmlpreview.github.io\/?https:\/\/github.com\/SengerM\/html-github-hosting\/blob\/main\/210202%20on%20the%20spacial%20characteristics%20of%20the%20TCT\/20210129171131_spagetti_y_scan\/processed_by_script_extract_beam_shape\/Estimated%20laser%20profile.html\" width=\"100%\" height=\"555\"><\/iframe>\n\n\n\n<p>This is, a Gaussian beam with  \\( \\sigma_\\text{laser} \\approx 9.1 \\text{ \u00b5m} \\).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusions<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n   <li>The spaghetti diode is a powerful tool to measure the spacial characteristics of the TCT.<\/li>\n   <li>The origin of the spacial jitter is not yet clear, some possible origins may be:\n   <ul>\n      <li>Errors in the positioning of the TCT stages.<\/li>\n      <li>The garbage on top of the spaghetti diode that I observed with the microscope.<\/li>\n      <li>Others?<\/li>\n   <\/ul>\n   <\/li>\n   <li>The shape of the laser is, to a first approximation, Gaussian with a standard deviation of about 9 \u00b5m.<\/li>\n   <li>All this analysis was done in the \\( y \\) direction, it is probably symmetric for \\( x \\) but we cannot ensure this right now.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>We are using our Particulars scanning TCT to characterize the spacial resolution of different devices. But, what is the spacial resolution of the TCT itself? What is the size and shape of the beam spot in the surface of the silicon? Spacial scan with the spaghetti diode Though there is not much documentation on the &hellip;<\/p>\n<p class=\"read-more\"> <a class=\"\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/a-spacial-characterization-of-the-tct\/\"> <span class=\"screen-reader-text\">A spacial characterization of the TCT<\/span> Read More &raquo;<\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":234,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"inline_featured_image":false,"footnotes":""},"categories":[1],"tags":[5,4],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/220"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=220"}],"version-history":[{"count":33,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/220\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":685,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/220\/revisions\/685"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/234"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=220"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=220"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=220"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}